    <div class="camps">
      <!-- Warm camp -->
      <div class="camp camp-warm">
        <div class="camp-header">
          <div class="camp-title">What survives of bitcoin's nature</div>
          <div class="camp-subtitle">the properties the Foundations pages describe</div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="bearer">
          <div class="dimension-name">Bearer status &amp; counterparty chain<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Nearly all US securities are held in "street name": the legal owner of record is Cede &amp; Co., the nominee of the Depository Trust Company. What you hold at a broker is a <em>security entitlement</em> &mdash; a claim on a chain of intermediaries &mdash; not the asset itself. Bitcoin held with your own keys has no chain: possession of the key <strong>is</strong> ownership.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="warm"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="confiscation">
          <div class="dimension-name">Confiscation reach &mdash; the 6102 test<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Executive Order 6102 (1933) required delivery of gold coin, bullion, and certificates to the Federal Reserve at $20.67/oz, under criminal penalty. It succeeded largely through banks and paper claims &mdash; the state seized ledgers, not living rooms. The test for any asset: does confiscating it take a memo, or a door?</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="warm"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="freezes">
          <div class="dimension-name">Freezes &amp; capital controls<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">A freeze order works by instructing an <em>intermediary</em> &mdash; a bank, broker, or exchange &mdash; to stop honoring your claims. Capital controls (Greece 2015, Argentina's cepo, Cyprus 2013) work the same way. An asset with no intermediary has no one to receive the order.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="warm"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="rehypo">
          <div class="dimension-name">Rehypothecation &amp; encumbrance<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Rehypothecation: a custodian lending or pledging "your" asset to someone else, so multiple claims point at the same coin. Proof-of-reserves attests to a snapshot of holdings; it cannot prove the absence of competing claims. On-chain coins under your keys are verifiably unencumbered &mdash; nothing moves without your signature.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="warm"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="privacy">
          <div class="dimension-name">Privacy of ownership records<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">KYC ("know your customer") rules pair your legal identity, address, and holdings in databases held by every regulated intermediary you touch. The record outlives the account &mdash; and as the France kidnapping wave showed, leaked records are how criminals choose doors.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="warm"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Cool camp -->
      <div class="camp camp-cool">
        <div class="camp-header">
          <div class="camp-title">What life requires of you</div>
          <div class="camp-subtitle">the burdens and risks you carry in exchange</div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="keyloss">
          <div class="dimension-name">Key loss &amp; recourse<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">A seed phrase is the human-readable backup of a private key. There is no password reset on the Bitcoin network &mdash; no company, court, or miner can restore a lost key. An estimated 2.3&ndash;4 million coins are already permanently inaccessible, mostly through ordinary human error.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="cool"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="coercion">
          <div class="dimension-name">Physical coercion &mdash; the wrench<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">The "$5 wrench attack": skipping the cryptography and attacking the person. France recorded dozens of crypto-linked abductions in a single recent year &mdash; roughly a quarter of the world's documented cases. The targeting came from leaked customer records, not from the blockchain.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="cool"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="inheritance">
          <div class="dimension-name">Inheritance<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">In traditional finance, a beneficiary designation and a death certificate transfer an account &mdash; heirs never touch the machinery. Self-custodied bitcoin inverts this: the secrecy that protects you in life can lock out your family at death, unless the handoff is engineered in advance.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="cool"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="burden">
          <div class="dimension-name">Operational burden<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">"Being your own bank" means being your own security, compliance, and disaster-recovery team: devices, backups, firmware, operational secrecy &mdash; sustained for decades, without a serious mistake. The burden is real, which is why every layer of help exists &mdash; and why each one costs a property.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="cool"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="dimension" data-dim="exit">
          <div class="dimension-name">Exit &amp; optionality<span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Selling an ETF in a taxable account is a taxable event; withdrawing your own coins from an exchange to your own wallet is not &mdash; you're moving property you already own. Only Authorized Participants (large broker-dealers) can redeem ETF shares for actual bitcoin; retail holders can only sell.</span></span></div>
          <div class="dimension-scale" data-camp="cool"></div>
          <div class="dimension-desc"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid-legend">
      <span class="legend-warm">Warm rows: how intact the property remains.</span>
      <span class="legend-cool">Cool rows: how heavy the burden you carry.</span>
      <span class="legend-note">No column wins. The question is which column's costs you can live with.</span>
