  <!-- §D — Optionality -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2>The cul-de-sac and the open door</h2>
    <p>The exchange holder and the ETF holder look similar &mdash; both trusted a third party with the keys. But one bought a position with an exit, and one bought a position with a toll booth on the exit. A holder of coins at an exchange who decides, next year or next decade, to take real custody makes one withdrawal: a network fee, no taxable event, done &mdash; they are moving property they already own. The ETF holder in a taxable account must sell (and recognize every dollar of gain), transfer the cash, rebuy the coins across a second spread, and then withdraw. Retail in-kind redemption does not exist: since mid-2025, redeeming shares for actual bitcoin is permitted &mdash; but only for Authorized Participants, in baskets of tens of thousands of shares. For everyone else, the only door out of the ETF is the sale.</p>
    <p>There is one honest exception, and it deserves plain statement: inside an IRA or 401(k), the ETF is not a cul-de-sac but the only road. It is the sole practical way to hold bitcoin exposure in the accounts where many people keep most of their wealth, with tax-deferred or tax-free compounding that nothing on this page can match. The price is the wrapper's own rules &mdash; required minimum distributions, and the permanent impossibility of ever taking coins in kind. For some readers that trade is right. It should simply be made knowingly.</p>
    <p>Optionality, in other words, is itself a property. The exchange account &mdash; the baby step &mdash; preserves your future self's ability to choose. The ETF quietly spends it.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- §E — The records -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2>The risk that follows the records</h2>
    <p>Here is the honest complication, and it cuts against this page's own grain. France has become the world's center of "wrench attacks" &mdash; physical coercion against bitcoin holders &mdash; with dozens of abductions in a single recent year, roughly a quarter of the world's documented cases: a hardware-wallet founder's finger severed for ransom, a CEO's daughter nearly taken in daylight, families targeted at home. And the leak vectors were not blockchains. They were <em>databases</em>: a hardware-wallet vendor's 2020 breach exposing 270,000 names and home addresses; a French crypto-tax platform's 2026 breach exposing 50,000 users' balances; a tax official reportedly selling state-held data to the gangs; ordinary bragging on social media.</p>
    <p><strong>Physical risk follows the records of ownership, not the location of the coins.</strong> Your keys can be mathematically unbreakable while your shipping address is not. This has implications the grid states plainly: the ETF genuinely mitigates the wrench &mdash; there is no bearer asset to hand over at gunpoint, and no presence in crypto-vendor databases. A single hardware wallet genuinely concentrates it &mdash; the key's holder <em>is</em> the vault's door. And multisig structurally dissolves it: with keys split across locations &mdash; or with a service holding one &mdash; no single person, including the owner under duress, can move the coins, and time-delays and duress protocols exist for precisely this attack.</p>
    <p>The dimension where paper is strongest and the dimension where it is weakest are different dimensions. That is the grid's whole point.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- §F — The steelman -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2>The steelman</h2>
    <p>The strongest case against self-custody deserves full volume: cryptographic sovereignty is incompatible with human fallibility. An estimated 2.3 to 4 million coins &mdash; somewhere between a tenth and a fifth of all the bitcoin that will ever exist &mdash; are already permanently lost. Not confiscated. Not stolen from exchanges. Lost: failed backups, forgotten phrases, estates that died with their owners. For a holder who cannot guarantee flawless operational security across decades &mdash; or whose family cannot navigate a hardware wallet under grief &mdash; the statistical risk of self-inflicted loss can genuinely exceed the risk of institutional failure. Anyone who tells you otherwise is selling certainty they don't have.</p>
    <p>But notice what this argument actually proves. Every coin in that graveyard was lost to a <em>single point of failure</em> &mdash; one phrase, one device, one person's memory. The argument is not for paper; it is for engineering the single point of failure away, which is exactly what multisig is. A two-of-three quorum survives a lost key, a house fire, a death &mdash; with a service holding one key, it survives them with guidance; built yourself, it survives them with discipline. The choice was never sovereignty <em>or</em> safety. That framing was an artifact of the single-key era, and the era is over.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- §G — Closing -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2>One event, two outcomes</h2>
    <p>Canada, February 2022. One government order under the Emergencies Act. Within days, exchanges froze accounts linked to the protests &mdash; no court order required &mdash; while self-custodied coins kept moving through the same blockade, because there was no one to receive the instruction. Same week, same country, same asset, opposite outcomes. It is the cleanest natural experiment custody has ever produced.</p>
    <p>And it sits on a century of precedent. 1933: paper claims and centralized custody made gold seizable by memo. Cyprus, 2013: uninsured bank deposits were legally converted into shares of the failing banks that held them &mdash; the bail-in moved from theory to template, and is now codified resolution policy on both sides of the Atlantic. Celsius, 2023: a bankruptcy court found that the platform's terms of service had legally transferred $4.2 billion of customers' coins to the platform &mdash; what they owned was an IOU, and they learned it in court. The pattern across a hundred years is consistent: <em>claims on assets are raw material for crisis resolution; bearer assets are not.</em></p>
    <p>Which makes the game theory worth stating &mdash; as inference, clearly labeled, but tight inference. A modern 6102 could capture only the paper quadrants. Announcing it would catalyze migration into the one quadrant it cannot reach, and jurisdictional flight by holders whose asset boards the plane with them. The order would strengthen the very thing it targets &mdash; which is precisely what 1933's order did not do, because gold had nowhere to go. An attack that advertises its own escape route is an attack a rational state hesitates to launch. And the quiet corollary: the more bitcoin sits in paper form, the cheaper and more rational that order becomes. Every self-custodied coin raises its price. Custody is not only a personal risk decision; it is a vote on whether the attack is worth attempting at all.</p>
    <p>Walk the warm rows of the grid one last time. Only self-custodied bitcoin retains the full set of properties the Foundations pages describe &mdash; bearer status, freeze immunity, border portability, unconfiscatability in practice. Gold held those properties in theory and lost them in practice, because self-custody of gold never scaled. Bitcoin is the first money whose physical form is <em>practical</em> &mdash; which means that, for the first time in monetary history, the properties are optional rather than theoretical. Every custody layer is a decision to decline them.</p>
    <p class="closing-line">6102 caught gold in the vault and gold in the hand.<br>It can catch bitcoin only on paper.</p>
  </section>

